# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 29 LIBRARIES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 29TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 28 to 29 documented libraries
# (commando via videocms).  New leaderboard: Rust=29, Go=29 (TWO-WAY TIE),
# TypeScript-Node=28.  Taxonomy now spans 226 cross-language CLI library
# variants across 54 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS thatisuday/commando AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 29TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# commando (https://github.com/thatisuday/commando, 140+ stars) is **Uday
# Hiwarale's (thatisuday) easy-to-use Go CLI application builder**.  Uday
# is a Mumbai-based Go infrastructure author known for educational content
# on Medium.  commando is the high-level CLI framework half of a two-part
# library family:
#
#   * thatisuday/clapper — low-level "getopt(3)"-style argv parser
#   * thatisuday/commando — high-level CLI app builder (built on clapper)
#
# Both are distributed as separate npm-style separated packages — commando
# imports clapper but each is independently versionable.
#
# commando is DISTINCT from every other documented Go CLI library on SIX
# specific axes:
#
#   1. PACKAGE-LEVEL FLUENT BUILDER — commando exposes its API as
#      PACKAGE-LEVEL functions returning a singleton:
#         commando.
#             SetExecutableName("reactor").
#             SetVersion("v1.0.0").
#             SetDescription("React project manager.")
#
#         commando.
#             Register("build").
#             SetShortDescription("build project").
#             AddArgument("name", "project name", "").
#             AddFlag("dir,d", "output dir", commando.String, ".").
#             SetAction(handler)
#
#         commando.Parse(nil)
#      No explicit App/Cli/Parser instantiation — the package itself is
#      the CLI builder, holding global state for the program.  Compare:
#        cobra:           NewRootCmd() + Execute()
#        urfave/cli:      cli.NewApp() + Run()
#        kong (R465):     kong.New() + Parse()
#        go-arg (R475):   arg.MustParse(&struct)
#        mow.cli (R470):  cli.App() + Run()
#        opts (R479):     opts.New(&struct) + Parse()
#        commando (THIS): commando.* (package singleton)
#      The PACKAGE-LEVEL pattern is rare in modern Go — most libraries
#      moved to explicit constructors after the early flag-stdlib era.
#      commando deliberately resurrects the simpler approach.
#
#   2. `Register(nil)` FOR ROOT COMMAND — commando's `Register()` function
#      uses `nil` as the sentinel for the ROOT command:
#         commando.Register(nil)              // root command
#         commando.Register("build")           // sub-command
#      Most Go CLI libraries use either a separate `Root()` method or
#      treat the root as a special "first command" — commando's `nil`
#      sentinel is uniquely Go-idiomatic.
#
#   3. `:` NAMESPACE SEPARATOR IN SUBCOMMAND NAMES — commando's example
#      usage (and videocms's actual usage) shows:
#         Register("serve:main")
#         Register("create:user")
#         Register("delete:user")
#      The colon is treated as a PATH SEPARATOR in the subcommand name,
#      letting commando display these as a grouped namespace in help
#      output ("create:" group with "user" subcmd; "delete:" group).
#      This is the FIRST documented Go CLI library with colon-namespaced
#      subcommands.  Compare cobra (subcommands are tree of Command
#      objects), urfave/cli (subcommands are nested struct fields).
#
#   4. STRING-KEYED MAP HANDLER — handler signature is:
#         func(args  map[string]commando.ArgValue,
#               flags map[string]commando.FlagValue)
#      Both args and flags are STRING-KEYED MAPS rather than typed
#      structs.  This is similar to Whiley's wycc.util.OptArg (R469)
#      Map<String,Object> result but in Go.  Type recovery requires
#      `flags["dir"].Value` accessor calls.  Trade-off: less type-safe
#      than struct-tag approaches but more flexible for dynamic
#      sub-command dispatch.
#
#   5. INVERTED FLAGS via `no-` PREFIX — `AddFlag("no-clean", ..., Bool,
#      true)` declares a flag `--no-clean` whose presence inverts the
#      default `true` to `false`.  The flag value is stored under the
#      key WITHOUT the `no-` prefix.  This is similar to Kong's
#      `negatable:""` tag (R465) but expressed as a NAMING CONVENTION
#      rather than a tag.  Niche but real.
#
#   6. VARIADIC ARGUMENTS via `...` SUFFIX — `AddArgument("files...", ...)`
#      makes `files` absorb all remaining positional arguments and
#      concatenate them with commas.  The COMMA-CONCATENATION choice
#      is unusual — most Go CLI libraries store variadic args as `[]string`.
#      commando's comma-joining means the caller must split the string
#      back into individual values.
#
# THE commando API SURFACE (verbatim from videocms usage)
#
#   import "github.com/thatisuday/commando"
#
#   func main() {
#       commando.
#           SetExecutableName("videocms").
#           SetVersion("v1.0.0").
#           SetDescription("Videocms cli - To manage your instances.")
#
#       commando.
#           Register(nil).  // root command
#           SetAction(func(args map[string]commando.ArgValue,
#                          flags map[string]commando.FlagValue) {
#               fmt.Println("try the help command")
#           })
#
#       commando.
#           Register("serve:main").
#           SetShortDescription("starts the main server").
#           SetAction(handlerFn)
#
#       commando.
#           Register("config").
#           SetShortDescription("prints the current configuration").
#           SetAction(configHandler)
#
#       commando.
#           Register("create:user").
#           SetShortDescription("creates a new user").
#           SetAction(createUserHandler)
#
#       commando.
#           Register("delete:user").
#           SetShortDescription("delete a user").
#           SetAction(deleteUserHandler)
#
#       commando.Parse(nil)
#   }
#
# Common method calls:
#   commando.SetExecutableName(name)         — program name in help
#   commando.SetVersion(ver)                  — for --version
#   commando.SetDescription(desc)             — for --help
#   commando.Register(name|nil)               — register subcommand
#   commando.Parse(argv|nil)                  — parse os.Args (or arbitrary)
#
# On the returned *Command:
#   .SetDescription(text)                     — long description
#   .SetShortDescription(text)                — short description
#   .AddArgument(name, desc, default)         — positional argument
#   .AddFlag(name+aliases, desc, type, def)   — flag
#   .SetAction(handler)                       — register handler fn
#
# Flag type constants:
#   commando.Bool                             — boolean
#   commando.Int                              — integer
#   commando.String                           — string
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER GO CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * flag (stdlib), cobra, pflag, urfave/cli v1/v2/v3, kingpin, kong R465,
#     go-flags, mitchellh/cli, akamensky/argparse, google/subcommands,
#     docopt.go, pborman/getopt, muesli/coral R441, containerd/cli R441,
#     go-prompt R451, readline R455 (mylg), opts R479 (cloud-torrent),
#     go-arg R475 (meshbird), mow.cli R470 (emitter), flaggy (_gurp),
#     go-getoptions R483 (NBIA), commando (THIS, package-level fluent
#                                          builder with colon-namespaced
#                                          subcommands)
#
# commando is the FIRST documented Go CLI library using PACKAGE-LEVEL
# SINGLETON BUILDER semantics.  Most Go CLI libraries explicitly
# instantiate a parser/app object; commando lets you skip the
# instantiation and chain straight off the package import.
#
